{"title_page": "Templeogue College", "text_new": "{{primary sources|date=April 2008}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name              = Templeogue College C.S.Sp\n| native_name       = Col\u00e1iste Theach Meal\u00f3g\n| logo              = \n| motto             = ''In Virtute Scientia''\n| motto_translation = Knowledge through virtue / Education Rooted In Values\n| established       = 1966\n| location          = [[Templeogue]], [[List of Dublin postal districts|Dublin 6W]]\n| country           = [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n| coordinates       = {{coord|53.3044|-6.3118|region:IE-D_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| students          = 650\n| principal         = Luke Philip Feely,the big willy champion \n| staff             = 42\n| free_label        = Religious institute\n| free_text         = [[Holy Ghost Fathers]]\n| homepage          = {{url|templeoguecollege.ie}}\n}}\n'''Templeogue College C.S.Sp''' is an [[Republic of Ireland|Irish]] [[voluntary secondary school|voluntary]] [[secondary school]] in the suburb of [[Templeogue]] in [[Dublin]]. It was founded in 1966 and is run by the [[Holy Ghost Fathers]], a [[Roman Catholic]] [[religious institute]].\n\nThe Latin motto of the school is ''In Virtute Scientia'' ('education rooted in virtue').\n\nThere are 650 pupils and 42 teachers.<ref>[http://www.templeoguecollege.ie/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=77&Itemid=76 ''School History '']. School website. Retrieved: 2010-10-01.</ref> The school rugby team (colours are red and blue) has reached the finals of the Leinster Schools Junior Cup twice, in 1980 and 1985,{{Citation needed|date=November 2010}} however, they were not successful. In 2002, a team visited [[South Africa]], the first state school in Ireland to do so.{{Citation needed|date=November 2010}}. The school is the only non-fee paying school to win the Leinster Schools' Senior League doing so in 2002 and the first school to win the inaugural Leinster Schools' Junior League in the 94/95 season.The school captured the Senior League (Level 2) now called Division 1B during the 2013/14 season. {{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nSports played at the school include [[rugby union]], [[basketball]], [[sport of athletics|athletics]], [[Gaelic football]], [[association football]], and [[hurling]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2007}} Sixty boys are involved in the school's concert band.\n\nIn 2016, the ''[[Irish Times]]'' listed Templeogue College as one of the top 25 non-fee paying schools in [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]], based on the proportion of students going on to university.\n\n==Alumni==\n{{unreferenced section|date=November 2016}}\n\n* [[Brendan Hyland]], International Swimmer\n* [[Eric O'Sullivan]], Ulster rugby union player \n* [[Lorcan Dempsey]], Vice President and Chief Strategist of OCLC\n* [[Diarmuid Gavin]], award-winning gardener TV personality\n* [[Morgan Kelly (Irish economist)]], Professor of Economics at UCD<ref>[http://www.irisheconomy.ie/index.php/2010/04/13/profile-of-morgan-kelly/ Profile of Morgan Kelly] IrishEconomy.ie, 2010-04-13.</ref>\n* [[Denis Bastick]], Gaelic footballer, [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]] inter-county team\n* [[Eoghan O'Gara]], Gaelic footballer, [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]] inter-county team\n* [[Malcolm O'Kelly]], former Irish international [[rugby union]] player\n* [[Dave McSharry]], [[Connacht Rugby|Connacht]] [[rugby union]] player\n* [[Enda Stevens]], (footballer) footballer with Sheffield United\n* [[Mick Pyro]], lead singer of the band [[Republic of Loose]]\n* [[Rob Rogers]], League of Ireland referee\n* [[Rob Smith (Irish musician)|Rob Smith]], indie musician and\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.templeoguecollege.ie/ School website]\n\n{{Spiritan secondary schools in Ireland}}\n{{Schools and colleges in County Dublin}}\n\n[[Category:Boys' schools in the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in South Dublin (county)]]\n[[Category:Catholic secondary schools in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Spiritan schools]]\n[[Category:Templeogue]]\n", "text_old": "{{primary sources|date=April 2008}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name              = Templeogue College C.S.Sp\n| native_name       = Col\u00e1iste Theach Meal\u00f3g\n| logo              = \n| motto             = ''In Virtute Scientia''\n| motto_translation = Knowledge through virtue / Education Rooted In Values\n| established       = 1966\n| location          = [[Templeogue]], [[List of Dublin postal districts|Dublin 6W]]\n| country           = [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n| coordinates       = {{coord|53.3044|-6.3118|region:IE-D_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| students          = 650\n| principal         = Luke Philip Feely\n| staff             = 42\n| free_label        = Religious institute\n| free_text         = [[Holy Ghost Fathers]]\n| homepage          = {{url|templeoguecollege.ie}}\n}}\n'''Templeogue College C.S.Sp''' is an [[Republic of Ireland|Irish]] [[voluntary secondary school|voluntary]] [[secondary school]] in the suburb of [[Templeogue]] in [[Dublin]]. It was founded in 1966 and is run by the [[Holy Ghost Fathers]], a [[Roman Catholic]] [[religious institute]].\n\nThe Latin motto of the school is ''In Virtute Scientia'' ('education rooted in virtue').\n\nThere are 650 pupils and 42 teachers.<ref>[http://www.templeoguecollege.ie/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=77&Itemid=76 ''School History '']. School website. Retrieved: 2010-10-01.</ref> The school rugby team (colours are red and blue) has reached the finals of the Leinster Schools Junior Cup twice, in 1980 and 1985,{{Citation needed|date=November 2010}} however, they were not successful. In 2002, a team visited [[South Africa]], the first state school in Ireland to do so.{{Citation needed|date=November 2010}}. The school is the only non-fee paying school to win the Leinster Schools' Senior League doing so in 2002 and the first school to win the inaugural Leinster Schools' Junior League in the 94/95 season.The school captured the Senior League (Level 2) now called Division 1B during the 2013/14 season. {{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nSports played at the school include [[rugby union]], [[basketball]], [[sport of athletics|athletics]], [[Gaelic football]], [[association football]], and [[hurling]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2007}} Sixty boys are involved in the school's concert band.\n\nIn 2016, the ''[[Irish Times]]'' listed Templeogue College as one of the top 25 non-fee paying schools in [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]], based on the proportion of students going on to university.\n\n==Alumni==\n{{unreferenced section|date=November 2016}}\n\n* [[Brendan Hyland]], International Swimmer\n* [[Eric O'Sullivan]], Ulster rugby union player \n* [[Lorcan Dempsey]], Vice President and Chief Strategist of OCLC\n* [[Diarmuid Gavin]], award-winning gardener TV personality\n* [[Morgan Kelly (Irish economist)]], Professor of Economics at UCD<ref>[http://www.irisheconomy.ie/index.php/2010/04/13/profile-of-morgan-kelly/ Profile of Morgan Kelly] IrishEconomy.ie, 2010-04-13.</ref>\n* [[Denis Bastick]], Gaelic footballer, [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]] inter-county team\n* [[Eoghan O'Gara]], Gaelic footballer, [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]] inter-county team\n* [[Malcolm O'Kelly]], former Irish international [[rugby union]] player\n* [[Dave McSharry]], [[Connacht Rugby|Connacht]] [[rugby union]] player\n* [[Enda Stevens]], (footballer) footballer with Sheffield United\n* [[Mick Pyro]], lead singer of the band [[Republic of Loose]]\n* [[Rob Rogers]], League of Ireland referee\n* [[Rob Smith (Irish musician)|Rob Smith]], indie musician and\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.templeoguecollege.ie/ School website]\n\n{{Spiritan secondary schools in Ireland}}\n{{Schools and colleges in County Dublin}}\n\n[[Category:Boys' schools in the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in South Dublin (county)]]\n[[Category:Catholic secondary schools in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Spiritan 